(86, 'INDIA GATE', 'A SYMBOL OF NATIONAL PRIDE', 'admin/monument-upload/INDIA GATE2.jpg', '7', 'Rajpath Marg, New Delhi', '<p>The India Gate is an iconic monument located in the heart of New Delhi, the capital city of India. Standing proudly at the eastern end of Rajpath, it serves as a symbol of the countrys rich history, cultural heritage, and national pride. This magnificent structure holds great significance and holds a special place in the hearts of Indians, serving as a prominent landmark and a popular tourist attraction.</p>  <p>The construction of the India Gate was completed in the year 1931 and it was designed by Sir Edwin Lutyens, a renowned British architect. The monument was originally known as the \"All India War Memorial\" and was built to commemorate the brave soldiers of the Indian Army who sacrificed their lives during World War I and the Third Anglo-Afghan War. It was later renamed as the India Gate in 1971, after India gained independence from British rule.</p>  <p>The India Gate is a massive sandstone archway that stands at a height of 42 meters (138 feet) and spans across a width of 9.1 meters (30 feet). It is inspired by the Arc de Triomphe in Paris and showcases a fusion of architectural styles, combining elements of both Indo-Islamic and Western design. The archway is adorned with intricate carvings and inscriptions, including the names of more than 13,000 Indian and British soldiers who lost their lives in the aforementioned wars.</p>  <p>Surrounding the India Gate is a large open area known as the \"Rajpath,\" which is a ceremonial boulevard extending from the Rashtrapati Bhavan (Presidential Residence) to the India Gate. This expansive green expanse serves as a popular spot for leisurely walks, picnics, and various recreational activities, especially during the evenings when the monument is beautifully illuminated.</p>  <p>Visitors to the India Gate can witness the eternal flame known as the \"Amar Jawan Jyoti\" (Flame of the Immortal Soldier), which burns day and night beneath the archway. This eternal flame serves as a tribute to the soldiers who sacrificed their lives for the nation and is a constant reminder of their bravery and selflessness.</p>  <p>The India Gate holds immense historical and cultural significance and has become a symbol of national unity and remembrance. It is a place where people gather to pay homage to the fallen soldiers, celebrate national events, and engage in patriotic fervor. The monument serves as a venue for various ceremonies and events, including the Republic Day Parade held annually on January 26th.</p>  <p>Overall, the India Gate stands as a majestic monument, a symbol of Indias past struggles and triumphs, and a testament to the bravery and sacrifice of its soldiers. It continues to be a cherished landmark that attracts millions of visitors, both locals and tourists, who are captivated by its grandeur, historical significance, and the patriotic spirit it represents.</p>', 'INR', '00', '00', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'New Delhi', 'Free', 'None', '00', '00', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
(87, 'QUTUB MINAR', 'A TIMELESS SYMBOL OF INDO-ISLAMIC ARCHITECTURE', 'admin/monument-upload/QUTUB MINAR2.jpg', '7', 'Mehrauli, New Delhi', '<p>Qutub Minar, located in Delhi, India, is an iconic UNESCO World Heritage Site and one of the tallest brick minarets in the world. Standing at a height of 73 meters (240 feet), it is an exceptional example of Indo-Islamic architecture. The construction of Qutub Minar was initiated in the early 12th century by Qutub-ud-din Aibak, the founder of the Delhi Sultanate, and was completed by his successors.</p>  <p>The minaret is comprised of five distinct stories, each adorned with intricately carved balconies and inscriptions from the Quran. The first three stories are built with red sandstone, while the fourth and fifth stories are made of marble and sandstone. The overall design showcases a fusion of Persian, Islamic, and Indian architectural styles.</p>  <p>Surrounding the Qutub Minar is the Qutub complex, which features several other historical structures, such as the Quwwat-ul-Islam Mosque, the Iron Pillar of Delhi, and various tombs and ruins. Visitors can explore the complex, admire the exquisite carvings and architectural details, and learn about the rich history and cultural significance of the site.</p>', 'INR', '30', '500', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'New Delhi', 'Paid', 'None', '30', '500', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
