id', 'None', '30', '500', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
(91, 'DIWAN-I-AAM', 'THE GRAND HALL OF PUBLIC AUDIENCE', 'admin/monument-upload/DIWAN-I-AAM2.jpg', '7', 'Opp Lal Qila, Old Delhi', '<p>Diwan-i-Aam, situated within the historic Red Fort in Delhi, India, is a magnificent hall that once served as the grand assembly area for public audiences during the Mughal era. It holds great historical and architectural significance, showcasing the grandeur and opulence of the Mughal Empire.</p>  <p>The hall, with its impressive dimensions and architectural details, was specifically designed to accommodate a large gathering of people. Constructed with red sandstone and adorned with intricate carvings and decorative motifs, it exudes an aura of regality and splendor.</p>  <p>At the center of the hall is a raised platform, where the emperors throne would be placed. The platform is beautifully embellished with marble inlays and delicate artwork, showcasing the artistic finesse of the Mughal craftsmen. The emperor would sit here to address the public, receive petitions, and dispense justice.</p>  <p>The halls architectural features are a visual treat. Its arches and columns are intricately carved with floral patterns, geometrical designs, and calligraphic inscriptions from the Quran. The ceilings are adorned with exquisite paintings, depicting scenes from Mughal court life and showcasing the empires cultural richness.</p>  <p>Diwan-i-Aam holds immense historical significance as it served as a symbolic space where the emperor connected with his subjects and demonstrated his authority and benevolence. It was a platform for public hearings, where people from all walks of life could present their grievances, seek redressal, and witness the grandeur of the imperial court.</p>  <p>Today, Diwan-i-Aam stands as a testament to the architectural brilliance and historical legacy of the Mughal Empire. Visitors can explore this majestic hall, marvel at its intricate craftsmanship, and imagine the grand gatherings that once took place within its walls, leaving a lasting impression of the opulent Mughal era.</p>', 'INR', '260', '260', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'New Delhi', 'Free', 'None', '260', '260', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
(92, 'SRI HARMANDIR SAHIB', 'THE ICONIC GOLDEN TEMPLE OF SIKHISM', 'admin/monument-upload/SRI HARMANDIR SAHIB2.jpg', '7', 'Amritsar, Punjab', '<p>Sri Harmandir Sahib, commonly known as the Golden Temple, is a revered and iconic Sikh gurdwara located in the city of Amritsar, Punjab, India. It holds a special place in the hearts of millions of Sikhs worldwide and serves as the central religious and cultural hub of Sikhism.</p>  <p>The gurdwaras architectural magnificence is breathtaking. Its prominent golden dome and gleaming exterior create a stunning sight, especially when illuminated at night. The temple stands amidst a serene complex that includes the sacred Amrit Sarovar, a large pool of holy water. Pilgrims from all walks of life visit this spiritual oasis to seek solace, pray, and connect with the divine.</p>  <p>Entering the Golden Temple complex, visitors are welcomed by the soothing sounds of hymns, or kirtan, which fill the air. The main entrance, known as the Darshani Deori, leads to the central courtyard where the temple stands. As per Sikh tradition, everyone is welcome irrespective of caste, creed, or gender.</p>  <p>The interior of Sri Harmandir Sahib is equally captivating. The sanctum sanctorum, also called the Darbar Sahib, houses the sacred scripture of Sikhism, the Guru Granth Sahib. Devotees gather here to offer their prayers and listen to the recitation of Gurbani (holy verses) performed by the Granthis (Sikh priests).</p>  <p>The temple complex is not just a place of worship but also a symbol of community service. The Guru-ka-Langar, a free community kitchen, serves meals to thousands of visitors every day, promoting equality and the spirit of seva (selfless service).</p>  <p>Sri Harmandir Sahib holds immense historical significance. It was founded by Guru Ram Das, the fourth Sikh Guru, in the 16th century and later expanded by Maharaja Ranjit Singh. The temple witnessed significant historical events, including the Jallianwala Bagh massacre in 1919.</p>  <p>Today, the Golden Temple is not only a sacred site but also a cultural and educational center. It houses museums, libraries, and educational institutions that preserve and promote Sikh history, literature, and arts.</p>  <p>The Golden Temple stands as a testament to the principles of Sikhism, including equality, service, and devotion. It continues to attract millions of pilgrims and visitors from all around the world, offering them a profound spiritual experience and a glimpse into the rich Sikh heritage.</p>', 'INR', '00', '00', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'Punjab', 'Free', 'None', '00', '00', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
(93, 'JALLIANWALA BAGH', 'REMEMBERING THE TRAGIC MASSACRE', 'admin/monument-upload/JALLIANWALA BAGH2.jpg', '7', 'Amritsar, Punjab', '<p>Jallianwala Bagh is a public garden located in Amritsar, Punjab, India. While it is known for its scenic beauty, it is also a place of historical significance due to the infamous Jallianwala Bagh massacre that occurred on April 13, 1919.</p>  <p>During the British colonial era, the Jallianwala Bagh was a gathering place for peaceful protests against the repressive Rowlatt Act. On that fateful day, British troops under the command of Brigadier General Reginald Dyer opened fire on a crowd of unarmed men, women, and children who had gathered for a public meeting. The merciless shooting continued for about ten minutes, resulting in the death of hundreds and injuring thousands.</p>  <p>The massacre sent shockwaves throughout India, leading to widespread outrage and marking a turning point in the Indian freedom struggle. It galvanized the fight for independence and fueled the non-violent resistance movement led by Mahatma Gandhi.</p>  <p>Today, Jallianwala Bagh stands as a memorial to the martyrs who lost their lives in the tragic incident. The garden has been preserved to retain its historical significance, with a memorial monument and plaques displaying the names of the victims. The bullet marks on the walls serve as a stark reminder of the brutality inflicted upon innocent people.</p>  <p>Visitors to Jallianwala Bagh can explore the park, paying their respects to the victims and reflecting on the sacrifices made during Indias struggle for freedom. The Martyrs Well, where many people jumped to escape the firing, remains a poignant reminder of the tragic events that unfolded.</p>  <p>Jallianwala Bagh stands not only as a symbol of remembrance but also as a reminder of the indomitable spirit and resilience of the Indian people. It is a place where visitors can reflect upon the past, honor the sacrifices of those who fought for freedom, and reaffirm their commitment to justice, equality, and peace.</p>', 'INR', '00', '00', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'Punjab', 'Free', 'None', '', '', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
(94, 'AKAL TAKHT', 'THE ETERNAL THRONE OF SIKHISM', 'admin/monument-upload/AKAL TAKHT2.jpg', '7', 'Golden Temple Complex, Punjab', '<p>Akal Takht, meaning Eternal Throne, is a significant religious and political institution in Sikhism. Located within the renowned Golden Temple Complex in Amritsar, Punjab, India, it holds the highest temporal authority in Sikhism. Akal Takht serves as the central platform for the Sikh community to address religious, social, and political matters.</p>  <p>The establishment of Akal Takht dates back to the time of Guru Hargobind Sahib, the sixth Sikh Guru, in the early 17th century. It was Guru Hargobind Sahib who constructed the elevated platform to symbolize the temporal power of the Sikh community alongside their spiritual authority.</p>  <p>The Akal Takht holds immense significance as a seat of power and justice. It represents the Sikh communitys sovereignty and acts as a forum for deliberations on religious doctrine, social issues, and community welfare. Decisions made at the Akal Takht are considered authoritative and binding for Sikhs worldwide.</p>  <p>Historically, the Akal Takht played a crucial role in shaping Sikh history and resistance against oppression. It provided a platform for Sikh leaders to address and mobilize the community during challenging times. The institution stood firm against injustice and upheld principles of equality, justice, and freedom.</p>  <p>Visiting Akal Takht offers a glimpse into the rich Sikh heritage and spirituality. The edifice is adorned with intricate architectural details, reflecting a blend of Mughal and Sikh architectural styles. The sanctum, adorned with religious insignia, represents the sanctity and authority of the Sikh tradition.</p>  <p>Moreover, Akal Takht is not just a physical structure; it is a symbol of Sikh resilience and unwavering commitment to social justice. It serves as a guiding force, reminding Sikhs of their duty to fight against oppression, defend human rights, and promote harmony and equality.</p>  <p>Akal Takht stands as a testament to the values and principles enshrined in Sikhism. It embodies the spirit of the Khalsa, the Sikh community, and remains a source of inspiration for Sikhs around the world. A visit to Akal Takht offers an opportunity to experience the profound spirituality and reverence that permeate the Golden Temple Complex, leaving visitors with a deep appreciation for Sikh traditions and teachings.</p>', 'INR', '00', '00', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'Punjab', 'Free', 'None', '00', '00', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100');
