(115, 'THIRUVALLUVAR STATUE', 'A Towering Tribute to Tamil Culture and Wisdom', 'admin/monument-upload/THIRUVALLUVAR STATUE2.jpg', '7', 'Valluvar Kottam Island Kanyakumari, Tamil Nadu', '<p>The Thiruvalluvar Statue is a magnificent monument situated on Valluvar Kottam Island in the enchanting town of Kanyakumari, Tamil Nadu, India. This iconic statue pays homage to the esteemed Tamil poet and philosopher, Thiruvalluvar, who is revered for his profound literary contributions and ethical teachings.</p>  <p>The Thiruvalluvar Statue stands tall and proud, overlooking the mesmerizing Bay of Bengal. It serves as a symbol of wisdom, knowledge, and cultural heritage, attracting visitors from all around the world. The statue is a striking representation of Thiruvalluvar, with its height of 133 feet, signifying the 133 chapters in his renowned literary work, the Thirukkural.</p>  <p>Constructed with sheer craftsmanship, the statue depicts Thiruvalluvar standing on a lotus-shaped pedestal, symbolizing purity and enlightenment. Clad in traditional attire, he holds a palm leaf manuscript, signifying his invaluable writings, in one hand, while the other hand rests gracefully on his chest, symbolizing his devotion to righteousness and humanity.</p>  <p>Reaching the Thiruvalluvar Statue involves a picturesque boat or ferry ride from the mainland to Valluvar Kottam Island. The island itself is a serene location that offers panoramic views of the azure ocean, creating a tranquil ambiance for visitors.</p>  <p>The Thiruvalluvar Statue is not just a marvel of architecture, but also an important cultural landmark. It serves as a reminder of the rich literary heritage of Tamil Nadu and honors the timeless wisdom and teachings of Thiruvalluvar. Visitors who come here are not only captivated by the beauty of the statue but also inspired by the poets profound philosophy, which promotes virtues such as love, righteousness, and non-violence.</p>  <p>Overall, the Thiruvalluvar Statue stands as a testament to the enduring legacy of Thiruvalluvar and continues to be a cherished attraction for those seeking knowledge, spirituality, and a deeper understanding of Tamil culture.</p>', 'INR', '20', '20', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'Tamil Nadu', 'Paid', 'None', '20', '20', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
(116, 'VIVEKANANDA ROCK MEMORIAL', 'A SERENE TRIBUTE TO SWAMI VIVEKANANDAS TEACHINGS', 'admin/monument-upload/VIVEKANANDA ROCK MEMORIAL2.jpg', '7', 'Kanyakumari, Tamil Nadu', '<p>The Vivekananda Rock Memorial is a revered monument located on the picturesque Vivekananda Rock in Kanyakumari, Tamil Nadu, India. It stands as a tribute to Swami Vivekananda, a prominent Indian philosopher and spiritual leader who played a significant role in the revival of Hinduism and the promotion of Vedanta philosophy.</p>  <p>The memorial is situated on a rocky island that is accessible via a short ferry or boat ride from the mainland. Upon reaching the rock, visitors are greeted by the majestic Vivekananda Rock Memorial, which exudes a sense of serenity and spirituality.</p>  <p>The architecture of the memorial is a blend of traditional and modern elements, reflecting the essence of Swami Vivekanandas teachings. The main structure consists of two main halls the Vivekananda Mandapam and the Shripada Mandapam.</p>  <p>The Vivekananda Mandapam is the central hall, featuring a life-size bronze statue of Swami Vivekananda in a meditative pose. The hall also houses a museum that showcases artifacts, photographs, and excerpts from his inspiring speeches. The museum provides visitors with a deeper understanding of Swami Vivekanandas life, his teachings, and his contributions to society.</p>  <p>The Shripada Mandapam is another important part of the memorial, which is believed to be the sacred spot where the footprints of the Goddess Kumari (the virgin goddess after whom Kanyakumari is named) are imprinted. The Shripada Mandapam is a place of reverence and serves as a symbol of the spiritual significance of the location.</p>  <p>Visiting the Vivekananda Rock Memorial is not just an architectural and historical experience but also a spiritual journey. The tranquil surroundings and the breathtaking views of the confluence of the Bay of Bengal, the Arabian Sea, and the Indian Ocean make it an ideal place for introspection and contemplation.</p>  <p>The Vivekananda Rock Memorial holds great significance for followers of Swami Vivekananda and spiritual seekers alike. It is a place where one can connect with the teachings and ideals of this revered spiritual leader, gaining inspiration and insight into the path of self-realization and service to humanity.</p>  <p>Overall, the Vivekananda Rock Memorial stands as a beacon of spirituality, enlightenment, and cultural heritage, inviting visitors from all corners of the world to experience the profound teachings and legacy of Swami Vivekananda.</p>', 'INR', '20', '20', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'Tamil Nadu', 'Paid', 'None', '20', '20', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
(117, 'PADMANABHAPURAM PALACE', 'A Timeless Masterpiece of Wooden Splendor', 'admin/monument-upload/PADMANABHAPURAM PALACE2.jpg', '7', 'Kanyakumari, Tamil Nadu', '<p>The Padmanabhapuram Palace, situated in the town of Padmanabhapuram, Tamil Nadu, India, is a magnificent wooden palace that stands as a testament to the rich cultural heritage and architectural grandeur of the region. This well-preserved palace offers a captivating journey back in time, allowing visitors to immerse themselves in the opulence and beauty of a bygone era.</p>  <p>The palace complex is spread over several acres and is renowned for its intricate woodwork, which is a masterpiece of craftsmanship. Every nook and corner of the palace showcases the impeccable skills of artisans who painstakingly carved wood into exquisite designs and motifs. The walls, ceilings, and pillars adorned with intricate carvings leave visitors awe-struck with their intricate detailing.</p>  <p>As visitors explore the palace, they are greeted with a series of interconnected rooms and courtyards, each with its own unique charm and purpose. The main attractions include the Kings Council Chamber, the Queen Mothers Palace, the Mantrasala (where the king conducted official meetings), the Thai Kottaram (the queens palace), and the Natakasala (the performance hall).</p>  <p>One of the standout features of the Padmanabhapuram Palace is the stunning collection of murals adorning the walls. These intricate paintings depict mythological stories, scenes from daily life, and exquisite portraits. The vibrant colors and intricate brushwork of these murals provide a glimpse into the artistic finesse of the time.</p>  <p>The palace also houses a museum that showcases a variety of artifacts and antiquities, including weapons, musical instruments, antique furniture, and traditional Kerala-style lamps. These artifacts offer insights into the royal lifestyle and cultural traditions of the era, enriching the visitors understanding of the historical significance of the palace.</p>  <p>Stepping into the serene courtyards of the Padmanabhapuram Palace, visitors can experience a sense of tranquility and splendor. The well-manicured gardens, with their lush greenery and neatly arranged plants, create a peaceful atmosphere for leisurely strolls.</p>  <p>The Padmanabhapuram Palace stands not just as a magnificent architectural marvel, but also as a living testament to the rich heritage and cultural legacy of the region. It serves as a window into the royal past, allowing visitors to appreciate the artistry, craftsmanship, and grandeur that once graced the lives of the kings and queens who resided within its walls.</p>  <p>Overall, a visit to the Padmanabhapuram Palace offers a delightful journey into the past, where history, art, and culture come together in perfect harmony, providing a memorable experience for all who step through its ornate gates.</p>', 'INR', '35', '300', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'Tamil Nadu', 'Paid', 'Closed on Mondays', '35', '300', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
(118, 'ALAMPARAI FORT', 'A Historic Ruin Amidst Coastal Beauty', 'admin/monument-upload/ALAMPARAI FORT2.jpg', '7', 'Villupuram, Tamil Nadu', '<p>The Alamparai Fort, situated in Kadappakkam village near Marakkanam in Tamil Nadu, India, is a fascinating historical site that bears witness to the regions rich past. Although now in ruins, the fort continues to captivate visitors with its intriguing history and picturesque coastal location.</p>  <p>The origins of the Alamparai Fort date back to the 17th century when it was constructed by the Nawab of Carnatic, under the reign of the Mughal Empire. The fort served as a strategic outpost for trade and defense along the Coromandel Coast.</p>  <p>The fortification was constructed using bricks and mortar, and its design incorporated both European and indigenous architectural elements. It featured bastions, watchtowers, and a large entrance gate that provided access to the forts interior.</p>  <p>Alamparai Fort once housed a thriving port that facilitated trade with various foreign powers. It was a bustling hub for commerce, particularly in salt production and shipping activities. The fort played a crucial role in the regions economy during its heyday.</p>  <p>Today, the Alamparai Fort stands in ruins, with only remnants of its former grandeur visible. The fort walls, partially intact, offer a glimpse into its original structure. Visitors can explore the weathered ramparts and marvel at the architectural remnants that tell stories of its past significance.</p>  <p>The forts coastal setting adds to its allure, with the expansive Bay of Bengal stretching out before it. The serene surroundings create a tranquil ambiance, making it a popular destination for nature lovers and history enthusiasts alike.</p>  <p>Visiting the Alamparai Fort provides an opportunity to delve into the history of the region and imagine the vibrant life that once thrived within its walls. It is a place where the echoes of past trade and cultural exchange can still be felt.</p>  <p>While the fort itself does not charge an entry fee, it is essential to note that it is located in a remote area. Visitors are advised to plan their trip in advance, considering transportation options and ensuring adequate provisions for a comfortable visit.</p>  <p>Overall, the Alamparai Fort stands as a silent witness to the regions bygone era, offering visitors a chance to explore its history, appreciate its architectural remnants, and soak in the beauty of its coastal surroundings.</p>', 'INR', '00', '00', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'Tamil Nadu', 'Free', 'None', '00', '00', 'Active', '100', '50', '100');
