(124, 'AGRA FORT', 'A MAGNIFICENT MUGHAL STRONGHOLD', 'admin/monument-upload/AGRA FORT2.jpg', '7', 'Agra, Uttar Pradesh', '<p>Agra Fort, located in Agra, Uttar Pradesh, India, is a historic fortress that served as the main residence of the Mughal emperors. Built using red sandstone, the fort is an architectural marvel that reflects the grandeur and opulence of the Mughal era.</p>  <p>The fort complex is spread over a vast area and features various structures, including palaces, mosques, courtyards, and gardens. Its striking architecture combines elements of Islamic, Persian, and Hindu styles, creating a unique blend of artistic influences.</p>  <p>Within the fort, visitors can explore the impressive structures, such as the Jahangiri Mahal, Khas Mahal, Diwan-i-Aam, Diwan-i-Khas, and Sheesh Mahal. These palaces showcase intricate carvings, beautiful marble work, and elaborate ornamentation.</p>  <p>The forts strategic location on the banks of the Yamuna River offers stunning views of the Taj Mahal. The Amar Singh Gate, facing the Taj Mahal, provides a breathtaking perspective of the iconic mausoleum.</p>  <p>Agra Fort has witnessed significant historical events and has been a symbol of power and authority throughout history. It served as the seat of power for various Mughal emperors, including Akbar, Jahangir, Shah Jahan, and Aurangzeb.</p>  <p>Recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage site, Agra Fort is not only a testament to architectural brilliance but also holds immense historical and cultural significance. It attracts tourists from around the world who come to admire its impressive structures and learn about Indias rich history.</p>  <p>Visiting Agra Fort allows visitors to step back in time and experience the magnificence of the Mughal Empire. The forts intricate design, captivating stories, and panoramic views make it a must-visit destination for history enthusiasts and architecture admirers.</p>', 'INR', '40', '550', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'Uttar Pradesh', 'Paid', 'None', '40', '550', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
(125, 'FATEHPUR SIKRI FORT', 'A MAGNIFICENT BLEND OF ARCHITECTURE AND HISTORY', 'admin/monument-upload/FATEHPUR SIKRI FORT2.jpg', '7', 'Fatehpur Sikri, Uttar Pradesh', '<p>Fatehpur Sikri Fort, situated in Fatehpur Sikri, Uttar Pradesh, India, is a remarkable historical fort renowned for its magnificent architecture and cultural significance. Constructed during the 16th century under the reign of Emperor Akbar, the fort showcases an amalgamation of Islamic, Persian, and Hindu architectural styles.</p>  <p>The fort complex spans over a vast area and features grand courtyards, palaces, mosques, and other structures. It served as the capital of the Mughal Empire for a short period before being abandoned, making it a fascinating glimpse into Mughal history.</p>  <p>One of the main attractions within the fort is the Buland Darwaza, an imposing gateway that stands as a symbol of victory. It is intricately designed with intricate carvings and inscriptions, and it leads to the Jama Masjid, a stunning mosque within the complex.</p>  <p>The fort also houses notable structures like the Diwan-i-Khas (Hall of Private Audience) and the Diwan-i-Aam (Hall of Public Audience). These structures are known for their architectural finesse, intricate detailing, and historical significance.</p>  <p>Additionally, Fatehpur Sikri Fort is home to several palaces, including the Panch Mahal, Birbals House, and Jodha Bais Palace. These palaces exhibit exquisite craftsmanship, beautiful frescoes, and splendid views of the surrounding landscape.</p>  <p>Fatehpur Sikri Forts architectural grandeur and historical significance have earned it the status of a UNESCO World Heritage site. Visitors to the fort can immerse themselves in the rich cultural heritage, marvel at the stunning craftsmanship, and explore the intriguing stories behind its creation.</p>  <p>The fort continues to captivate travelers from around the world, serving as a testament to the glorious Mughal era. Fatehpur Sikri Fort stands as a magnificent architectural masterpiece, preserving the legacy of an empire and offering an unforgettable experience for history enthusiasts and architecture aficionados alike.</p>', 'INR', '35', '550', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'Uttar Pradesh', 'Paid', 'None', '35', '550', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
(126, 'KANS QILA', 'A MAGNIFICENT FORT OF MYTHOLOGY AND HISTORY', 'admin/monument-upload/KANS QILA2.jpg', '7', 'Mathura, Uttar Pradesh', '<p>Kans Qila, located in Uttar Pradesh, India, is a remarkable historical fort steeped in mythological significance. Revered in Hindu mythology as the birthplace of Lord Krishna, it holds a special place in the hearts of devotees and visitors alike. This magnificent fort is adorned with architectural splendor, showcasing the rich cultural heritage of the region.</p>  <p>The stories and legends associated with Kans Qila add an air of enchantment to its already captivating allure. According to popular belief, it was within the walls of this fort that Lord Krishna, the eighth incarnation of Lord Vishnu, was born. The fort thus became an emblematic site for devotees, drawing pilgrims from far and wide who seek to pay homage and experience the divine aura surrounding this sacred place.</p>  <p>As one approaches Kans Qila, the imposing structure commands attention. Its architectural grandeur showcases a blend of artistic styles from different eras, reflecting the rich historical legacy of Uttar Pradesh. The intricate carvings, ornate arches, and sturdy walls stand as a testament to the craftsmanship of ancient artisans. Exploring the forts sprawling complex offers visitors a glimpse into the opulent lifestyle of the rulers of that era.</p>  <p>Stepping inside Kans Qila is like stepping into a realm where history and mythology intertwine. The fort resonates with echoes of the past, immersing visitors in a sense of awe and wonder. The various chambers, courtyards, and temples within the fort complex evoke a sense of serenity, transporting visitors to a bygone era. Each nook and corner holds secrets and untold tales, waiting to be discovered by those curious enough to explore.</p>  <p>Today, Kans Qila is not only a religious site but also a popular tourist attraction. Its cultural and historical significance draws a large number of visitors who come to witness its magnificence and pay homage to Lord Krishna. The fort stands as a symbol of pride for the people of Uttar Pradesh, preserving the heritage and spirituality associated with the birthplace of a revered deity.</p>  <p>Visiting Kans Qila is an experience that transcends time. It allows one to delve into the mystical realms of mythology and history while appreciating the architectural brilliance of ancient times. The forts enduring legacy and its ability to captivate the hearts and minds of visitors make it an extraordinary destination that leaves a lasting impression.</p>', 'INR', '00', '00', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'Uttar Pradesh', 'Free', 'None', '00', '00', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
(127, 'AKBARS TOMB', 'A MAJESTIC MAUSOLEUM OF MUGHAL SPLENDOR', 'admin/monument-upload/AKBARS TOMB2.jpg', '7', 'Agra, Uttar Pradesh', '<p>Akbars Tomb, situated in Sikandra, Agra, Uttar Pradesh, is an awe-inspiring mausoleum that stands as a testament to the grandeur of Emperor Akbar, one of the most influential rulers of the Mughal Empire. This architectural masterpiece holds immense historical and cultural significance, drawing visitors from far and wide.</p>  <p>The tomb complex is a harmonious blend of different architectural styles, reflecting the diverse cultural influences of the Mughal era. The main mausoleum is a colossal structure made of red sandstone and marble, showcasing intricate carvings and inlaid work. Its magnificent dome, rising to an impressive height, is a prominent feature that adds to the regal charm of the monument.</p>  <p>Exploring the tomb complex reveals a meticulously designed layout with beautiful gardens, pathways, and water features. The charbagh (four-quartered) style of garden design, typical of Mughal architecture, creates a serene ambiance, enhancing the overall splendor of the site. These meticulously maintained gardens provide a tranquil space for visitors to relax and soak in the architectural magnificence.</p>  <p>The interior of Akbars Tomb reflects the artistic finesse of the Mughal craftsmen. Intricate marble work, delicate inlays, and exquisite geometric patterns adorn the walls and ceilings. The tomb chamber houses the cenotaph of Emperor Akbar, intricately carved with verses from the Quran and adorned with floral motifs. The serene atmosphere within the tomb evokes a sense of reverence and pays homage to the great emperor.</p>  <p>Akbars Tomb not only serves as a mausoleum but also as a monument of historical and cultural importance. It offers a glimpse into the rich history and architectural brilliance of the Mughal Empire. The tomb complex also houses other structures, including the tomb of Akbars daughter, Mariam-uz-Zamani, and a mosque.</p>  <p>Visiting Akbars Tomb is a captivating experience that transports visitors back in time, allowing them to appreciate the grandeur and legacy of Emperor Akbar. The monument stands as a tribute to his vision and accomplishments, leaving a lasting impression on all who visit.</p>', 'INR', '20', '200', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'Uttar Pradesh', 'Paid', 'None', '20', '200', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
(128, 'METCALFE HALL', 'A GRAND MONUMENT OF CULTURAL HERITAGE IN KOLKATA', 'admin/monument-upload/METCALFE HALL2.jpg', '7', 'Malda, West Bengal', '<p>Metcalfe Hall, located in Kolkata, West Bengal, India, is a historic and iconic building that stands as a symbol of architectural grandeur and cultural heritage. Constructed in the 19th century, it is named after Lord Metcalfe, the Governor-General of India during that time.</p>  <p>The hall showcases an elegant fusion of classical Greek and Roman architectural styles. Its impressive colonnaded facade, with tall Corinthian pillars and ornate detailing, captivates the attention of onlookers. The majestic entrance and the intricate embellishments reflect the architectural brilliance of the era.</p>  <p>Metcalfe Hall is not only renowned for its architectural splendor but also for its cultural significance. The hall serves as a cultural center, hosting a range of events, exhibitions, and programs that celebrate art, literature, and history. It houses a library that holds a treasure trove of books, manuscripts, and rare documents, attracting scholars and researchers.</p>  <p>Visiting Metcalfe Hall offers a unique opportunity to immerse oneself in the rich history and heritage of Kolkata. The spacious interiors feature grand halls adorned with chandeliers, period furniture, and exquisite artwork. The serene atmosphere and the sense of antiquity create an ambiance that transports visitors to a bygone era.</p>  <p>The hall also houses various galleries that showcase art exhibitions, displaying the works of renowned artists as well as local talents. These exhibitions provide a platform for art enthusiasts and contribute to the promotion of artistic expression and creativity.</p>  <p>Metcalfe Hall stands as a testimony to the cultural legacy of Kolkata and serves as a reminder of its colonial past. Its strategic location in the heart of the city makes it easily accessible to visitors who wish to explore and appreciate its architectural beauty and cultural offerings.</p>  <p>For those interested in history, art, and culture, a visit to Metcalfe Hall is a captivating experience. It allows one to delve into the historical narratives of the region, appreciate the artistic masterpieces, and gain a deeper understanding of Kolkatas rich cultural tapestry.</p>', 'INR', '00', '00', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'West Bengal', 'Free', 'None', '00', '00', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
(129, 'EKLAKHI MAUSOLEUM', 'AN ARCHITECTURAL GEM OF CULTURAL SIGNIFICANCE', 'admin/monument-upload/EKLAKHI MAUSOLEUM2.jpg', '7', 'Malda district, West Bengal', '<p>Eklakhi Mausoleum, located in Pandua, Malda district, West Bengal, India, is an intriguing historical monument that holds significant architectural and cultural value. This exquisite mausoleum showcases a distinctive octagonal shape and intricate terracotta ornamentation, making it a captivating sight for visitors.</p>  <p>The mausoleum stands as a testament to the rich cultural heritage of the region. Its octagonal design sets it apart from other structures of its time, lending it a unique and intriguing character. Each side of the mausoleum features intricate terracotta carvings that depict various scenes from mythology, religious motifs, and floral patterns.</p>  <p>Stepping inside Eklakhi Mausoleum is like stepping into a world of artistic marvels. The interior walls are adorned with more terracotta embellishments, showcasing the skill and craftsmanship of the artisans who created them. The intricate details and patterns tell stories of the past, providing a glimpse into the cultural and historical influences of the era.</p>  <p>Eklakhi Mausoleum is a testament to the architectural brilliance of the region, as well as the artistic and cultural exchange that took place during its construction. It showcases a fusion of Islamic and indigenous architectural elements, reflecting the diverse influences that shaped the regions heritage.</p>  <p>Visiting Eklakhi Mausoleum is a journey through time, allowing visitors to appreciate the beauty and craftsmanship of a bygone era. It offers a serene and contemplative atmosphere, inviting visitors to reflect on the rich history and cultural legacy of the region.</p>  <p>The mausoleum serves as a reminder of the vibrant past and the architectural treasures that exist in West Bengal. Its unique design, intricate terracotta work, and historical significance make it an important landmark for history enthusiasts, art lovers, and those interested in exploring the cultural heritage of the region.</p>  <p>Eklakhi Mausoleum stands as a testament to the artistic and cultural brilliance of the past, providing a glimpse into the diverse and rich history of the Malda district. It continues to captivate visitors with its architectural splendor and intricate detailing, making it a must-visit destination for those seeking to delve into the regions cultural tapestry.</p>', 'INR', '00', '00', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'West Bengal', 'Free', 'None', '00', '00', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
(130, 'HAZARDUARI PALACE', 'A GLIMPSE INTO ROYAL SPLENDOR', 'admin/monument-upload/HAZARDUARI PALACE2.jpg', '7', 'Murshidabad, West Bengal', '<p>The Hazarduari Palace, located in Murshidabad, West Bengal, India, is an iconic historical landmark renowned for its architectural splendor and rich heritage. Constructed during the 19th century, this magnificent palace is characterized by its remarkable design, featuring a thousand doors, of which around 900 are functional entrances.</p> <p>The palace served as the official residence of the Nawabs of Bengal and witnessed significant historical events during their rule. It stands as a testament to the grandeur and opulence of the bygone era. Today, the Hazarduari Palace has been transformed into a museum, attracting visitors from around the world who are intrigued by its captivating history and artifacts.</p> <p>As visitors explore the palace-turned-museum, they are transported back in time to experience the regal lifestyle of the Nawabs. The museum houses a vast collection of artifacts, including exquisite artworks, weaponry, manuscripts, costumes, and other relics, offering a glimpse into the cultural, artistic, and political aspects of the era.</p> <p>Each room within the palace tells a unique story, preserving the memories and traditions of the Nawabs. The intricate carvings, stunning archways, and spacious halls leave visitors in awe, providing an immersive experience of the rich architectural heritage of the region.</p> <p>Surrounded by sprawling gardens and situated on the banks of the Bhagirathi River, the Hazarduari Palace showcases a harmonious blend of Indo-European architectural styles. Its strategic location near the river adds to its scenic beauty, creating a serene and picturesque setting.</p> <p>Whether one is a history enthusiast, an art lover, or simply seeking to admire the architectural marvels of the past, the Hazarduari Palace offers a captivating journey into the royal history of Bengal. It stands as a proud symbol of the regions cultural legacy, inviting visitors to explore its grand halls and corridors while unraveling the captivating tales of the Nawabs.</p>', 'INR', '20', '250', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'West Bengal', 'Paid', 'Closed on Fridays', '20', '250', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
(131, 'SAHID MINAR', 'A TRIBUTE TO COURAGE AND FREEDOM', 'admin/monument-upload/SAHID MINAR2.jpg', '7', 'Kolkata, West Bengal', '<p>The Shaheed Minar, also known as the Martyrs Monument, is an iconic structure located in Kolkata, West Bengal, India. It stands as a poignant tribute to the brave souls who sacrificed their lives for Indias independence.</p> <p>The construction of the Shaheed Minar dates back to the early 19th century when it was originally erected in memory of Major General Sir David Ochterlony, a distinguished British military officer. However, after India gained independence in 1947, the monument was rededicated to honor the martyrs who fought for the countrys freedom.</p> <p>The Shaheed Minar stands tall at a height of 48 meters (157 feet) and showcases a unique blend of architectural styles, combining elements of both Indo-Islamic and Gothic revival influences. The structure is adorned with intricate ornamentation and features a spiral staircase leading to an observation platform at the top.</p> <p>Visitors to the Shaheed Minar can ascend the staircase to enjoy panoramic views of the surrounding cityscape. The monument holds a significant place in the hearts of Kolkata residents, serving as a symbol of courage, sacrifice, and the indomitable spirit of freedom.</p> <p>Throughout the year, the Shaheed Minar serves as a focal point for various cultural and social gatherings. It is particularly illuminated during important national events and festivals, further enhancing its majestic presence and reminding people of the sacrifices made by those who fought for Indias freedom.</p> <p>The Shaheed Minar has become an iconic landmark of Kolkata, attracting tourists and locals alike. It not only symbolizes the struggles of the past but also stands as a reminder of the aspirations and dreams of a nation striving for progress, unity, and the preservation of its hard-fought independence.</p>', 'INR', '00', '00', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'West Bengal', 'Free', 'None', '00', '00', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100'),
(132, 'ARCHAEOLOGICAL SITE MUSEUM', 'PRESERVING THE PAST', 'admin/monument-upload/ARCHAEOLOGICAL SITE MUSEUM2.jpg', '7', 'Tamluk, West Bengal', '<p>The Archaeological Site Museum in West Bengal is a treasure trove of historical artifacts and archaeological findings that provide insights into the regions rich cultural heritage. This museum serves as a custodian of the past, preserving and displaying a wide range of objects that have been excavated from various archaeological sites.</p> <p>Inside the museum, visitors can explore a fascinating collection that includes ancient sculptures, pottery, coins, tools, jewelry, and other archaeological relics. Each artifact tells a story of the bygone civilizations that once thrived in the region, offering a window into their way of life, beliefs, and artistic expressions.</p> <p>Walking through the exhibits, visitors can witness the evolution of art, architecture, and craftsmanship over different periods of history. The museum showcases artifacts from different eras, spanning from prehistoric times to medieval and beyond, showcasing the cultural diversity and historical significance of West Bengal.</p> <p>The Archaeological Site Museum also plays a vital role in educating the public about the importance of archaeological research and conservation. It serves as a platform for scholars, researchers, and enthusiasts to study and interpret the findings, unraveling the mysteries of the past and contributing to our understanding of human history.</p> <p>With its curated displays and informative exhibits, the museum offers an immersive experience, transporting visitors back in time. It fosters a sense of appreciation for the intricate craftsmanship, artistic achievements, and technological advancements of ancient civilizations.</p> <p>Moreover, the Archaeological Site Museum serves as a cultural hub, hosting workshops, seminars, and lectures to promote archaeological awareness and engage with the local community. It strives to bridge the gap between the past and the present, fostering a sense of pride and connection to the regions heritage.</p> <p>Whether one is a history enthusiast, an art lover, or simply curious about the ancient past, the Archaeological Site Museum in West Bengal is a captivating destination. It allows visitors to delve into the rich tapestry of the regions history, offering a glimpse into the remarkable achievements and legacies of those who came before us.</p>', 'INR', '5', '5', 'Per Person', 'Morning to Night', 'West Bengal', 'Paid', 'Closed on Fridays', '5', '5', 'Active', '1000', '50', '100');
